first1=Lars\n|last2=Lund\n|first2=J\u00f8rn\n|year=1974\n|title=Udtaleforskelle i Danmark\n|publisher=Gjellerup\n|place=Copenhagen\n|isbn=978-8713019465\n}}\n* {{citation\n|last=Fischer-J\u00f8rgensen\n|first=Eli\n|authorlink=Eli Fischer-J\u00f8rgensen\n|year=1972\n|chapter=Formant Frequencies of Long and Short Danish Vowels\n|editor1-last=Scherabon Firchow\n|editor1-first=Evelyn\n|editor2-last=Grimstad\n|editor2-first=Kaaren\n|editor3-last=Hasselmo\n|editor3-first=Nils\n|editor4-last=O'Neil\n|editor4-first=Wayne A.\n|title=Studies for Einar Haugen: Presented by Friends and Colleagues\n|location=The Hague\n|publisher=Mouton\n|pages=189\u2013213\n|isbn=978-90-279-2338-7\n|doi=10.1515/9783110879131-017\n}}\n* {{citation\n|last=Gr\u00f8nnum\n|first=Nina\n|author-link=Nina Gr\u00f8nnum\n|year=1992\n|title=The groundworks of Danish intonation\n|publisher=Museum Tusculanum Press\n|place=Copenhagen\n|isbn=978-8772891699\n}}\n* {{citation\n|last=Gr\u00f8nnum\n|first=Nina\n|year=1996\n|title=Danish vowels \u2013 scratching the recent surface in a phonological experiment\n|journal=Acta Linguistica Hafniensia\n|volume=28\n|pages=5\u201363\n|doi=10.1080/03740463.1996.10416062\n|url=https://danpass.hum.ku.dk/ng/papers/acta_28_1996_5-63.pdf\n}}\n* {{citation\n|last=Gr\u00f8nnum\n|first=Nina\n|year=1998\n|chapter=Intonation in Danish\n|editor1-last=Hirst\n|editor1-first=Daniel\n|editor2-last=Di Cristo\n|editor2-first=Albert\n|title=Intonation Systems: A Survey of Twenty Languages\n|isbn=0-521-39513-5\n|ref=none\n}}\n* {{citation\n|last=Gr\u00f8nnum\n|first=Nina\n|year=2007\n|title=R\u00f8dgr\u00f8d med fl\u00f8de \u2013 En lille bog om dansk fonetik\n|publisher=Akademisk Forlag\n|place=Copenhagen\n|isbn=978-87-500-3918-1\n}}\n* {{citation\n|last=Heger\n|first=Steffen\n|year=1981\n|title=Sprog og lyd \u2013 Element\u00e6r dansk fonetik\n|edition=2nd\n|location=Copenhagen\n|publisher=Gjellerup\n|isbn=87-500-3089-2\n}}\n* {{citation\n|last1=Lundsk\u00e6r-Nielsen\n|first1=Tom\n|last2=Barnes\n|first2=Michael\n|last3=Lindskog\n|first3=Annika\n|year=2005\n|title=Introduction to Scandinavian phonetics: Danish, Norwegian, and Swedish\n|publisher=Alfabeta\n|isbn=978-8763600095\n}}\n* {{citation\n|last=Molb\u00e6k Hansen\n|first=Peter\n|year=1990\n|title=Udtaleordbog\n|publisher=Gyldendal\n|place=Copenhagen\n|isbn=978-87-02-05895-6\n}}\n{{refend}}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://sproghistorie.dk/lydsystem/ Overview of the Danish sound system] {{spoken}}\n\n{{Danish language}}\n{{Language phonologies}}\n\n[[Category:Language phonologies]]\n[[Category:Danish language|phonology]]\n", "text_old": "{{selfref|For assistance with IPA transcriptions of Danish for Wikipedia articles, see [[Help:IPA/Danish]]. For the transcription system based on the Danish orthography, see [[Dania transcription]].}}\n{{IPA notice}}\n\nThe [[phonology]] of [[Danish language|Danish]] is similar to that of the other closely related [[North Germanic languages|Scandinavian languages]], [[Swedish language|Swedish]] and [[Norwegian language|Norwegian]], but it also has distinct features setting it apart. For example, Danish has a [[suprasegmental]] feature known as [[st\u00f8d]] which is a kind of laryngeal phonation that is used phonemically. It also exhibits extensive [[lenition]] of plosives, which is noticeably more common than in the neighboring languages. Because of that and a few other things, spoken Danish is rather hard to understand for Norwegians and Swedes, although they can easily read it.\n\n== Consonants ==\nDanish has at least 17 [[consonant]] [[phoneme]]s:\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align: center;\"\n!\n! [[Bilabial consonant|Bilabial]]\n! [[Labiodental consonant|Labio-<br />dental]]\n! [[Alveolar consonant|Alveolar]]\n! [[Palatal consonant|Palatal]]\n! [[Velar consonant|Velar]]\n! [[Uvular consonant|Uvular]]\n! [[Glottal consonant|Glottal]]\n|-\n! [[Nasal consonant|Nasal]]\n| {{IPA link|m}}\n|\n| {{IPA link|n}}\n|\n| {{IPA link|\u014b}}\n|\n|\n|-\n! [[Plosive]]\n| {{IPA link|p}}&nbsp;&nbsp;{{IPA link|p|b}}\n|\n| {{IPA link|ts|t}}&nbsp;&nbsp;{{IPA link|t|d}}\n|\n| {{IPA link|k}}&nbsp;&nbsp;{{IPA link|k|\u0261}}\n|\n|\n|-\n! [[Fricative]]\n|\n| {{IPA link|f}}\n| {{IPA link|s}}\n| ({{IPA link|\u0255}})\n|\n|\n| {{IPA link|h}}\n|-\n! [[Approximant]]\n|\n| {{IPA link|\u028b|v}}\n| {{IPA link|\u00f0\u0320\u02d5|\u00f0}}\n| {{IPA link|j}}\n| ({{IPA link|w}})\n| {{IPA link|\u0281|r}}\n|\n|-\n! [[Lateral consonant|Lateral]]\n|\n|\n| {{IPA link|l}}\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|}\n\n{| class=\"wikitable floatright\" style=\"text-align: center;\"\n|+ [[Phone (phonetics)|Phone]]\u2013[[phoneme]]\u2013[[morphophoneme]] correspondence{{sfnp|Basb\u00f8ll|2005|pp=75\u20136, 547}}\n! rowspan=\"2\" | Phone\n! rowspan=\"2\" | Phoneme\n! colspan=\"2\" | Morphophoneme\n|-\n! Syllable-<br />initial\n! Syllable-<br />final\n|-\n| {{IPA|[m]}}\n| {{IPA|/m/}}\n| colspan=\"2\" | {{IPA|&#124;m&#124;}}\n|-\n| {{IPA|[n]}}\n| {{IPA|/n/}}\n| colspan=\"2\" | {{IPA|&#124;n&#124;}}\n|-\n| {{IPA|[\u014b]}}\n| {{IPA|/\u014b/}}\n| {{n/a}}\n| {{IPA|&#124;n\u0261&#124;}}, {{IPA|&#124;\u014b&#124;}},{{efn|In French loans and the suffixes ''{{nowrap|-ing}}, {{nowrap|-ling}}, {{nowrap|-ning}}''.}} <br />{{IPA|&#124;n&#124;}}{{efn|Before {{IPA|&#124;k&#124;}}.}}\n|-\n| {{IPA|[p\u02b0]}}\n| {{IPA|/p/}}\n| {{IPA|&#124;p&#124;}}\n| {{n/a}}\n|-\n| {{IPA|[ts\u02b0]}}\n| {{IPA|/t/}}\n| {{IPA|&#124;t&#124;}}\n| {{n/a}}\n|-\n| {{IPA|[k\u02b0]}}\n| {{IPA|/k/}}\n| {{IPA|&#124;k&#124;}}\n| {{n/a}}\n|-\n| {{IPA|[p]}}\n| {{IPA|/b/}}\n| {{IPA|&#124;b&#124;}}\n| {{IPA|&#124;p, b&#124;}}\n|-\n| {{IPA|[t]}}\n| {{IPA|/d/}}\n| {{IPA|&#124;d&#124;}}\n| {{IPA|&#124;t&#124;}}\n|-\n| {{IPA|[k]}}\n| {{IPA|/\u0261/}}\n| {{IPA|&#124;\u0261&#124;}}\n| {{IPA|&#124;k&#124;}}\n|-\n| {{IPA|[f]}}\n| {{IPA|/f/}}\n| colspan=\"2\" | {{IPA|&#124;f&#124;}}\n|-\n| {{IPA|[s]}}\n| {{IPA|/s/}}\n| colspan=\"2\" | {{IPA|&#124;s&#124;}}\n|-\n| {{IPA|[\u0255]}}\n| {{IPA|/sj/}}\n| colspan=\"2\" | {{IPA|&#124;sj&#124;}}{{efn|In native words, syllable-initial only.}}\n|-\n| {{IPA|[h]}}\n| {{IPA|/h/}}\n| {{IPA|&#124;h&#124;}}\n| {{n/a}}\n|-\n| {{IPA|[v]}}\n| {{IPA|/v/}}\n| {{IPA|&#124;v&#124;}}\n| {{n/a}}\n|-\n| {{IPA|[\u00f0]}}\n| {{IPA|/\u00f0/}}\n| {{n/a}}\n| {{IPA|&#124;d&#124;}}\n|-\n| {{IPA|[j]}}\n| {{IPA|/j/}}\n| {{IPA|&#124;j&#124;}}\n| {{IPA|&#124;j, \u0261&#124;}}\n|-\n| {{IPA|[w]}}\n| {{IPA|/v/}}\n| {{n/a}}\n| {{IPA|&#124;v, \u0261&#124;}}\n|-\n| {{IPA|[\u0281]}}\n| {{IPA|/r/}}\n| {{IPA|&#124;r&#124;}}\n| {{n/a}}\n|-\n| {{IPA|[\u0250\u032f]}}\n| {{IPA|/r/}}\n| {{n/a}}\n| {{IPA|&#124;r&#124;}}\n|-\n| {{IPA|[l]}}\n| {{IPA|/l/}}\n| colspan=\"2\" | {{IPA|&#124;l&#124;}}\n|-\n| colspan=\"4\" style=\"max-width: 20em;\" | {{notelist}}\n|}\n\n{{IPA|/p, t, k, h/}} occur only syllable-initially and {{IPA|[\u014b, \u00f0, w]}} only syllable-finally.{{sfnp|Basb\u00f8ll|2005|p=64}}{{sfnp|Gr\u00f8nnum|1998|pp=99-100}} {{IPA|[\u0255]}} is phonemically {{IPA|/sj/}} and {{IPA|[w]}} is the syllable-final allophone of {{IPA|/v/}}.{{sfnp|Basb\u00f8ll|2005|pp=64\u20135}} {{IPA|[w]}} also occurs syllable-initially in English loans, along with {{IPAblink|\u0279\u0320|\u0279}}, but syllable-initial {{IPA|[w]}} is in [[free variation]] with {{IPA|[v]}} and these are not considered part of the phonological inventory of Danish.{{sfnp|Basb\u00f8ll|2005|p=63}}\n\n{{IPA|/\u014b/}} occurs only before short vowels and stems [[morphophonology|morphophonologically]], in native words, from {{IPA|{{!}}n\u0261{{!}}}} or {{IPA|{{!}}n{{!}}}} preceding {{IPA|{{!}}k{{!}}}} and, in French loans, from a distinct {{IPA|{{!}}\u014b{{!}}}}. Beyond morphological boundaries, {{IPA|[\u014b]}} may also appear as the result of an optional assimilation of {{IPA|/n/}} before {{IPA|/k, \u0261/}}.{{sfnp|Basb\u00f8ll|2005|p=75}}\n\n{{IPA|/n, t, d, s, \u00f0, l/}} are apical alveolar,{{sfnp|Basb\u00f8ll|2005|pp=60\u20133, 131}} although some speakers realize {{IPA|/s/}} dentally ({{IPAblink|s\u032a}}).{{sfnp|Thorborg|2003|p=80|ps=. The author states that {{IPA|/s/}} is pronounced with \"the tip of the tongue right behind upper teeth, but without touching them.\" This is confirmed by the accompanying image.}}{{sfnp|Gr\u00f8nnum|2005|p=144|ps=. Only this author mentions both alveolar and dental realizations.}}\n\n{{IPA|/p, t, k/}} are [[voiceless]] [[Aspiration (phonetics)|aspirated]], with {{IPA|/t/}} also affricated: {{IPA|[p\u02b0, ts\u02b0, k\u02b0]}}.{{sfnp|Gr\u00f8nnum|2005|pp=120, 303\u20135}} {{IPA|/t/}} is often transcribed with {{angbr IPA|t\u02e2}}. In some varieties of standard Danish (but not the Copenhagen dialect), {{IPA|/t/}} is just aspirated, without the affrication.{{sfnp|Gr\u00f8nnum|2005|p=303}}\n\n{{IPA|/b, d, \u0261/}} are voiceless unaspirated {{IPA|[p, t, k]}}.{{sfnp|Gr\u00f8nnum|2005|pp=303\u20135}} In syllable codas, weak, partial voicing may accompany them especially when between voiced sounds.{{sfnp|Goblirsch|2018|pp=134\u20135|ps=, citing {{harvtxt|Fischer-J\u00f8rgensen|1952}} and {{harvtxt|Abrahams|1949|pp=116\u201321, 228\u201330}}.}} Utterance-final {{IPA|/b, d, \u0261/}} may be realized as {{IPA|[p\u02b0, t(s)\u02b0, k\u02b0]}}, particularly in distinct speech.{{sfnp|Basb\u00f8ll|2005|p=213}} Intervocalic {{IPA|/d/}} may be realized as a voiced flap {{IPAblink|\u027e}}, as in ''nor'''d'''isk'' {{IPA|[\u02c8no\u0250\u032f\u027eisk]}} 'Nordic'.{{sfnp|Gr\u00f8nnum|2005|p=157}}{{sfnp|Basb\u00f8ll|2005|p=126}}\n\n{{IPA|/h/}} is only weakly fricated.{{sfnp|Basb\u00f8ll|2005|pp=61\u20132}} Between vowels, it is often voiced {{IPAblink|\u0266}}.{{sfnp|Gr\u00f8nnum|2005|p=125}}\n\n{{IPA|/v/}} is most often a voiced approximant {{IPAblink|\u028b}}.{{sfnp|Basb\u00f8ll|2005|p=27}}\n\n{{IPA|/\u00f0/}} \u2013 the so-called \"soft d\" ({{lang-da|bl\u00f8dt d}}) \u2013 is a velarized laminal alveolar approximant {{IPAblink|\u00f0\u0320\u02d5|\u00f0\u0320\u02d5\u02e0}}.{{sfnp|Basb\u00f8ll|2005|pp=59, 63}}{{sfnp|Gr\u00f8nnum|2003|p=121}}{{sfnp|Ladefoged|Maddieson|1996|p=144}} It is acoustically similar to the cardinal vowels {{IPAblink|\u026f}} and {{IPAblink|\u0268}}.{{sfnp|Gr\u00f8nnum|2003|p=121}} It is commonly perceived by non-native speakers of Danish as {{IPAblink|l}}.{{sfnp|Haberland|1994|p=320}}{{sfnp|Gr\u00f8nnum|2003|p=121}} Very rarely, {{IPA|/\u00f0/}} can be realized as a fricative.{{sfnp|Ladefoged|Maddieson|1996|p=144}}\n\nSyllable-initially, {{IPA|/r/}} is a voiced uvular fricative {{IPAblink|\u0281}} or, more commonly, an approximant {{IPAblink|\u0281\u031e}}.{{sfnp|Basb\u00f8ll|2005|pp=62, 66}} According to [[Nina Gr\u00f8nnum]], the fricative variant is voiceless {{IPAblink|\u03c7}}.{{sfnp|Basb\u00f8ll|2005|p=62}} Its precise place of articulation has been described as pharyngeal,{{sfnp|Ladefoged|Maddieson|1996|p=323}} or more broadly, as \"supra-pharyngeal\".{{sfnp|Gr\u00f8nnum|1998|p=99}} When emphasizing a word, word-initial {{IPA|/r/}} may be realized as a voiced uvular fricative trill {{IPAblink|\u0280\u031d}}.{{sfnp|Gr\u00f8nnum|2005|p=157}} In syllable-final position, /\u0281/ is realized as [\u0250\u032f].{{sfnp|Basb\u00f8ll|2005|p=64}}\n\nThe alveolar realization {{IPAblink|r}} of {{IPA|/r/}} is very rare. According to {{harvp|Torp|2001}}, it occurs in some varieties of [[Jutlandic dialect]], and only for some speakers (mostly the elderly). The alveolar realization is considered non-standard, even in classical opera singing \u2013 it is probably the only European language in which this is the case.{{sfnp|Torp|2001|p=78}} According to {{harvp|Basb\u00f8ll|2005}}, it occurs (or used to occur until recently) in very old forms of certain conservative dialects in Northern Jutland and [[Bornholm dialect|Bornholm]].{{sfnp|Basb\u00f8ll|2005|p=218}}\n\n{{IPA|/l, j, r/}} are voiceless {{IPA|[{{IPAplink|l\u0325}}, {{IPAplink|\u00e7|\u029d\u030a}}~{{IPAplink|\u0255}}, {{IPAplink|\u03c7}}]}} after {{IPA|/p, t, k/}}, where the aspiration is realized as devoicing of the following consonant,{{sfnp|Basb\u00f8ll|2005|pp=65\u20136}} so that {{IPA|/tj/}} is normally realized as an alveolo-palatal affricate {{IPAblink|t\u0255}}.{{sfnp|Gr\u00f8nnum|2005|p=148}}\n\nA voiced velar continuant {{IPAblink|\u0263}} occurred distinctively in older Standard Danish. Some older speakers still use it in [[diglossia|high register]], most often as an approximant {{IPAblink|\u0263\u02d5}}.{{sfnp|Basb\u00f8ll|2005|pp=211\u20132}}{{sfnp|Gr\u00f8nnum|2005|p=123}} It corresponds to {{IPA|[w]}}, after back vowels and {{IPA|/r/}}, and to {{IPA|/j/}}, after front vowels and {{IPA|/l/}}, in contemporary Standard Danish.{{sfnp|Basb\u00f8ll|2005|pp=211\u20132}}\n\n{{IPA|/j/}} is elided after {{IPA|/i\u02d0, y\u02d0/}}, and possibly also after {{IPA|/e\u02d0, \u00f8\u02d0/}}, and less commonly after {{IPA|/\u025b\u02d0, a\u02d0/}}. Similarly, {{IPA|/v/}} is elided after {{IPA|/u\u02d0/}}, and possibly also after {{IPA|/o\u02d0/}}, and less commonly after {{IPA|/\u0254\u02d0/}}.{{sfnp|Gr\u00f8nnum|2005|p=296}}\n\n{{clear}}\n\n==Vowels==\n{{multiple image\n|image1=Danish vowel chart.svg\n|caption1=[[Monophthong]]s of Modern Standard Danish, from {{harvp|Gr\u00f8nnum|1998|p=100}}. Unstressed {{IPA|[\u026a, \u028a, \u0259, \u0250]}} are not shown. The distinction between {{IPA|[\u0153]}} and {{IPA|[\u0276]}} is optional.\n|image2=Conservative Standard Danish vowel chart.svg\n|caption2=Some of Conservative Standard Danish vowels shown on a vowel chart, from {{harvp|Ladefoged|Johnson|2010|p=227}}\n}}\nModern Standard Danish has around 20 different [[vowel]] qualities. These vowels are shown here in a narrow transcription.\n\n{{IPA|/\u0259/}} and {{IPA|/\u0250/}} occur only in unstressed syllables and thus can only be short. With the exception of {{IPA|/a/}}, {{IPA|/\u028c/}} and {{IPA|/\u0254\u02d0/}} all stressed vowels may be either long and short, including {{IPA|/a\u02d0/}} (only phonetically, it is mostly long though as its phonemic short counterpart is {{IPA|/a/}}). {{IPA|/\u028c/}} is always short, whereas its phonemic long counterpart {{IPA|/\u0254\u02d0/}} is mostly long, except before {{IPA|/\u00f0/}} (the short {{IPA|[\u0254\u031d]}} is an allophone of {{IPA|/o/}}). Long vowels may have [[Danish phonology#St.C3.B8d|st\u00f8d]],{{cn|date=January 2020}} thus making it possible to distinguish 30 different vowels in stressed syllables. However, vowel length and st\u00f8d are most likely features of the syllable rather than of the vowel.\n\nThese [[allophone]]s can be analyzed into 11 distinctive vowels, where allophonic alternation mainly depends on whether the vowel occurs before or after {{IPA|/r/}}.\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align: center;\"\n! rowspan=\"3\" |\n! colspan=\"4\" | [[Front vowel|Front]]\n! colspan=\"2\" rowspan=\"2\" | [[Central vowel|Central]]\n! colspan=\"2\" rowspan=\"2\" | [[Back vowel|Back]]\n|-\n! colspan=\"2\" | {{small|unrounded}}\n! colspan=\"2\" | {{small|rounded}}\n|-\n! {{small|short}}\n! {{small|long}}\n! {{small|short}}\n! {{small|long}}\n! {{small|short}}\n! {{small|long}}\n! {{small|short}}\n! {{small|long}}\n|-\n! [[Close vowel|Close]]\n| {{IPA link|i}}\n| {{IPA link|i\u02d0}}\n| {{IPA link|y}}\n| {{IPA link|y\u02d0}}\n|\n|\n| {{IPA link|u}}\n| {{IPA link|u\u02d0}}\n|-\n! [[Close-mid vowel|Close-mid]]\n| {{IPA link|e\u031d|e}}\n| {{IPA link|e\u031d|e\u02d0}}\n| {{IPA link|\u00f8}}\n| {{IPA link|\u00f8\u02d0}}\n| {{IPA link|\u0259}}\n|\n| {{IPA link|o}}\n| {{IPA link|o\u02d0}}\n|-\n! [[Open-mid vowel|Open-mid]]\n| {{IPA link|e|\u025b}}\n| {{IPA link|e\u02d0|\u025b\u02d0}}\n| {{IPA link|\u0153}}\n| {{IPA link|\u0153\u02d0}}\n| {{IPA link|\u0250}}\n|\n| {{IPA link|\u0252|\u028c}}\n| {{IPA link|\u0254\u031d|\u0254\u02d0}}\n|-\n! [[Open vowel|Open]]\n| {{IPA link|\u00e6|a}}\n| {{IPA link|\u025b\u02d0|a\u02d0}}\n|\n|\n| {{IPA link|\u0251\u0308|\u0251}}\n| {{IPA link|\u0251\u0308|\u0251\u02d0}}\n| {{IPA link|\u0252}}\n| {{IPA link|\u0252\u02d0}}\n|}\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"text-align: center;\"\n|+ [[Morphophoneme]]\u2013[[phoneme]]\u2013[[phone (phonetics)|phone]] correspondence{{sfnp|Basb\u00f8ll|2005|pp=45\u20137, 52, 57\u20139, 71, 546\u20137}}{{sfnp|Gr\u00f8nnum|2005|pp=36\u20137, 59\u201361, 287\u201392, 420\u20131}}\n! rowspan=\"2\" | Morpho-<br />phoneme\n! colspan=\"2\" | [[Tautosyllabic]] <br />environment\n! rowspan=\"2\" | Phoneme\n! rowspan=\"2\" | Phone\n! rowspan=\"2\" | Narrow <br />tran-<br />scription\n! rowspan=\"2\" | Example\n! rowspan=\"2\" class=\"unsortable\" | Note\n|-\n! After\n! Before\n|-\n| {{IPA|&#124;i&#124;}}\n|\n|\n| {{IPA|/i/}}\n| {{IPA|[i]}}\n| {{IPA|[i]}}\n| ''m'''i'''s''\n| style=\"text-align: left;\" |\n|-\n| {{IPA|&#124;i\u02d0&#124;}}\n|\n|\n| {{IPA|/i\u02d0/}}\n| {{IPA|[i\u02d0]}}\n| {{IPA|[i\u02d0]}}\n| ''m'''i'''le''\n| style=\"text-align: left;\" |\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\" | {{IPA|&#124;e&#124;}}\n|\n|\n| rowspan=\"2\" | {{IPA|/e/}}\n| {{IPA|[e\u031d]}}\n| {{IPA|[e\u031d]}}\n| ''l'''i'''st''\n| style=\"text-align: left;\" |\n|-\n| {{IPA|&#124;r&#124;}}\n|\n| {{IPA|[\u025b\u031d]}}\n| {{IPA|[\u025b\u031d]}}\n| ''br'''i'''st''\n| style=\"text-align: left;\" |\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\" | {{IPA|&#124;e\u02d0&#124;}}\n|\n|\n| {{IPA|/e\u02d0/}}\n| {{IPA|[e\u031d\u02d0]}}\n| {{IPA|[e\u031d\u02d0]}}\n| ''m'''e'''le''\n| style=\"text-align: left;\" |\n|-\n| {{IPA|&#124;r&#124;}}\n|\n| {{IPA|/\u025b\u02d0/}}\n| {{IPA|[\u025b\u031d\u02d0]}}\n| {{IPA|[\u025b\u031d\u02d0~\u025b\u031dj]}}\n| ''gr'''e'''ne''\n| style=\"text-align: left;\" |\n|-\n| rowspan=\"4\" | {{IPA|&#124;\u025b&#124;}}\n|\n|\n| rowspan=\"2\" | {{IPA|/\u025b/}}\n| {{IPA|[e]}}\n| {{IPA|[e]}}\n| ''l'''\u00e6'''st''\n| style=\"text-align: left;\" |\n|-\n|\n| {{IPA|&#124;r&#124;}}\n| {{IPA|[\u025b]}}\n| {{IPA|[\u025b]}}\n| ''b'''\u00e6'''r''\n| style=\"text-align: left;\" |\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\" | {{IPA|&#124;r&#124;}}\n| {{IPA|&#124;{{abbr|\u2205|Nothing}}, {{abbr|D|Dorsal (palatal, velar or uvular)}}&#124;}}\n| {{IPA|/\u025b/}} or {{IPA|/\u0251/}}\n| {{IPA|[\u00e6~\u0251]}}\n| {{IPA|[a~\u0251\u0308]}}\n| ''r'''\u00e6'''kke''\n| style=\"text-align: left;\" | {{IPA|[\u0251]}} in innovative varieties.{{sfnp|Basb\u00f8ll|2005|p=45}}\n|-\n|\n| {{IPA|/\u0251/}}\n| {{IPA|[\u0251]}}\n| {{IPA|[\u0251\u0308]}}\n| ''kr'''\u00e6'''ft''\n| style=\"text-align: left;\" |\n|-\n| rowspan=\"4\" | {{IPA|&#124;\u025b\u02d0&#124;}}\n|\n|\n| rowspan=\"3\" | {{IPA|/\u025b\u02d0/}}\n| {{IPA|[e\u02d0]}}\n| {{IPA|[e\u02d0]}}\n| ''m'''\u00e6'''le''\n| style=\"text-align: left;\" |\n|-\n|\n| {{IPA|&#124;r&#124;}}\n| {{IPA|[e\u02d0~\u025b\u02d0]}}\n| {{IPA|[e\u02d0~\u025b\u02d0]}}\n| ''b'''\u00e6'''re''\n| style=\"text-align: left;\" | {{IPA|[\u025b\u02d0]}} in innovative varieties.{{sfnp|Basb\u00f8ll|2005|p=149}}\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\" | {{IPA|&#124;r&#124;}}\n|\n| {{IPA|[\u025b\u031d\u02d0]}}\n| {{IPA|[\u025b\u031d\u02d0~\u025b\u031dj]}}\n| ''kr'''\u00e6'''se''\n| style=\"text-align: left;\" |\n|-\n| {{IPA|&#124;d&#124;}}\n| {{IPA|/a\u02d0/}} or {{IPA|/\u0251\u02d0/}}\n| {{IPA|[\u00e6\u02d0~\u0251\u02d0]}}\n| {{IPA|[\u00e6\u02d0~\u0251\u0308\u02d0]}}\n| ''gr'''\u00e6'''de''\n| style=\"text-align: left;\" | {{IPA|[\u0251\u02d0]}} in innovative varieties.{{sfnp|Gr\u00f8nnum|2005|p=285}}\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\" | {{IPA|&#124;a&#124;}}\n| \u2260 {{IPA|&#124;r&#124;}}\n| {{IPA|&#124;{{abbr|A|Alveolar}}&#124;}}\n| {{IPA|/a/}}\n| {{IPA|[\u00e6]}}\n| {{IPA|[\u00e6]}}\n| ''m'''a'''lle''\n| style=\"text-align: left;\" |\n|-\n|\n|\n| rowspan=\"2\" | {{IPA|/\u0251/}}\n| rowspan=\"2\" | {{IPA|[\u0251]}}\n| rowspan=\"2\" | {{IPA|[\u0251\u0308]}}\n| ''t'''a'''kke''\n| style=\"text-align: left;\" |\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\" | {{IPA|&#124;ar&#124;}}\n|\n| {{IPA|&#124;{{abbr|&#35;|Word boundary}}&#124;}}\n| ''v'''ar'''''\n| style=\"text-align: left;\" | Only in a handful of words.{{sfnp|Basb\u00f8ll|2005|p=154}}\n|-\n|\n|\n| {{IPA|/\u0251\u02d0/}}\n| {{IPA|[\u0251\u02d0]}}\n| {{IPA|[\u0251\u0308\u02d0]}}\n| '''''ar'''ne''\n| style=\"text-align: left;\" |\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\" | {{IPA|&#124;a\u02d0&#124;}}\n|\n|\n| {{IPA|/a\u02d0/}}\n| {{IPA|[\u025b\u02d0]}}\n| {{IPA|[\u025b\u02d0]}}\n| ''m'''a'''le''\n| style=\"text-align: left;\" |\n|-\n| {{IPA|&#124;r&#124;}}\n|\n| rowspan=\"2\" | {{IPA|/\u0251\u02d0/}}\n| rowspan=\"2\" | {{IPA|[\u0251\u02d0]}}\n| rowspan=\"2\" | {{IPA|[\u0251\u0308\u02d0]}}\n| ''tr'''a'''ne''\n| style=\"text-align: left;\" |\n|-\n| {{IPA|&#124;a\u02d0r&#124;}}\n|\n|\n| ''h'''ar'''''\n| style=\"text-align: left;\" |\n|-\n| {{IPA|&#124;y&#124;}}\n|\n|\n| {{IPA|/y/}}\n| {{IPA|[y]}}\n| {{IPA|[y]}}\n| ''l'''y'''t''\n| style=\"text-align: left;\" |\n|-\n| {{IPA|&#124;y\u02d0&#124;}}\n|\n|\n| {{IPA|/y\u02d0/}}\n| {{IPA|[y\u02d0]}}\n| {{IPA|[y\u02d0]}}\n| ''k'''y'''le''\n| style=\"text-align: left;\" |\n|-\n| rowspan=\"4\" | {{IPA|&#124;\u00f8&#124;}}\n|\n|\n| rowspan=\"2\" | {{IPA|/\u00f8/}}\n| {{IPA|[\u00f8]}}\n| {{IPA|[\u00f8]}}\n| ''k'''y'''s''\n| style=\"text-align: left;\" |\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\" | {{IPA|&#124;r&#124;}}\n| \u2260 {{IPA|&#124;v, j, \u0261&#124;}}\n| {{IPA|[\u0153\u031d~\u0153]}}\n| {{IPA|[\u0153\u031d~\u0153]}}\n| ''gr'''y'''nt''\n| style=\"text-align: left;\" | {{IPA|[\u0153]}} in innovative varieties.\n|-\n| {{IPA|&#124;v&#124;}}\n| {{IPA|/\u0153/}}\n| {{IPA|[\u0276]}}\n| {{IPA|[\u0276\u031d]}}\n| ''dr'''\u00f8'''v''\n| style=\"text-align: left;\" | {{sfnp|Brink|Lund|Heger|J\u00f8rgensen|1991|p=87}}\n|-\n|\n| {{IPA|&#124;j, \u0261&#124;}}\n| {{IPA|/\u028c/}}\n| {{IPA|[\u028c]}}\n| {{IPA|[\u0252\u033d]}}\n| ''t'''\u00f8'''j''\n| style=\"text-align: left;\" |\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\" | {{IPA|&#124;\u00f8\u02d0&#124;}}\n|\n|\n| rowspan=\"2\" | {{IPA|/\u00f8\u02d0/}}\n| {{IPA|[\u00f8\u02d0]}}\n| {{IPA|[\u00f8\u02d0]}}\n| ''k'''\u00f8'''le''\n| style=\"text-align: left;\" |\n|-\n| {{IPA|&#124;r&#124;}}\n|\n| {{IPA|[\u0153\u031d\u02d0~\u0153\u02d0]}}\n| {{IPA|[\u0153\u031d\u02d0~\u0153\u02d0]}}\n| ''r'''\u00f8'''be''\n| style=\"text-align: left;\" | {{IPA|[\u0153\u02d0]}} in innovative varieties.\n|-\n| rowspan=\"3\" | {{IPA|&#124;\u0153&#124;}}\n|\n|\n| rowspan=\"3\" | {{IPA|/\u0153/}}\n| {{IPA|[\u0153\u031d]}}\n| {{IPA|[\u0153\u031d]}}\n| ''h'''\u00f8'''ns''\n| style=\"text-align: left;\" |\n|-\n|\n| {{IPA|&#124;r&#124;}}\n| {{IPA|[\u0153]}}\n| {{IPA|[\u0153]}}\n| ''g'''\u00f8'''r''\n| style=\"text-align: left;\" |\n|-\n| {{IPA|&#124;r&#124;}}\n|\n| {{IPA|[\u0276]}}\n| {{IPA|[\u0276\u031d]}}\n| ''gr'''\u00f8'''n''\n| style=\"text-align: left;\" |\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\" | {{IPA|&#124;\u0153\u02d0&#124;}}\n|\n|\n| rowspan=\"2\" | {{IPA|/\u0153\u02d0/}}\n| {{IPA|[\u0153\u031d\u02d0]}}\n| {{IPA|[\u0153\u031d\u02d0]}}\n| ''h'''\u00f8'''ne''\n| style=\"text-align: left;\" | Rare.{{sfnp|Brink|Lund|Heger|J\u00f8rgensen|1991|p=108}}\n|-\n|\n| {{IPA|&#124;r&#124;}}\n| {{IPA|[\u0153\u02d0]}}\n| {{IPA|[\u0153\u02d0]}}\n| ''g'''\u00f8'''re''\n| style=\"text-align: left;\" |\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\" | {{IPA|&#124;u&#124;}}\n|\n|\n| {{IPA|/u/}}\n| {{IPA|[u]}}\n| {{IPA|[u]}}\n| ''g'''u'''ld''\n| style=\"text-align: left;\" |\n|-\n| {{IPA|&#124;r&#124;}}\n|\n| {{IPA|/u/}}\n| {{IPA|[u~o]}}\n| {{IPA|[u~o\u031d]}}\n| ''br'''u'''sk''\n| style=\"text-align: left;\" | {{IPA|[o]}} in innovative varieties.{{sfnp|Basb\u00f8ll|2005|p=150}}\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\" | {{IPA|&#124;u\u02d0&#124;}}\n|\n|\n| {{IPA|/u\u02d0/}}\n| {{IPA|[u\u02d0]}}\n| {{IPA|[u\u02d0]}}\n| ''m'''u'''le''\n| style=\"text-align: left;\" |\n|-\n| {{IPA|&#124;r&#124;}}\n|\n| {{IPA|/u\u02d0/}} or {{IPA|/o\u02d0/}}\n| {{IPA|[u\u02d0~o\u02d0]}}\n| {{IPA|[u\u02d0~o\u031d\u02d0]}}\n| ''r'''u'''se''\n| style=\"text-align: left;\" | {{IPA|[o\u02d0]}} in innovative varieties.{{sfnp|Basb\u00f8ll|2005|p=150}}\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\" | {{IPA|&#124;o&#124;}}\n|\n| {{IPA|&#124;{{abbr|\u2205|Nothing}}, r&#124;}}\n| rowspan=\"2\" | {{IPA|/o/}}\n| {{IPA|[o]}}\n| {{IPA|[o\u031d]}}\n| ''s'''o'''rt'' ('black')\n| style=\"text-align: left;\" |\n|-\n|\n|\n| {{IPA|[\u0254\u031d]}}\n| {{IPA|[\u0254\u033d]}}\n| '''''o'''st'' ('cheese')\n| style=\"text-align: left;\" |\n|-\n| {{IPA|&#124;o\u02d0&#124;}}\n|\n|\n| {{IPA|/o\u02d0/}}\n| {{IPA|[o\u02d0]}}\n| {{IPA|[o\u031d\u02d0]}}\n| ''m'''o'''le''\n| style=\"text-align: left;\" |\n|-\n| {{IPA|&#124;\u0254&#124;}}\n|\n|\n| {{IPA|/\u028c/}}\n| {{IPA|[\u028c]}}\n| {{IPA|[\u0252\u033d]}}\n| ''m'''\u00e5'''tte''\n| style=\"text-align: left;\" |\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\" | {{IPA|&#124;\u0254r&#124;}}\n|\n| {{IPA|&#124;{{abbr|&#35;|Word boundary}}&#124;}}\n| {{IPA|/\u0252/}}\n| {{IPA|[\u0252]}}\n| {{IPA|[\u0252\u031d]}}\n| ''v'''or'''''\n| style=\"text-align: left;\" | Only in a handful of words.{{sfnp|Basb\u00f8ll|2005|p=154}}\n|-\n|\n|\n| rowspan=\"2\" | {{IPA|/\u0252\u02d0/}}\n| rowspan=\"2\" | {{IPA|[\u0252\u02d0]}}\n| rowspan=\"2\" | {{IPA|[\u0252\u031d\u02d0]}}\n| ''m'''or'''se''\n| style=\"text-align: left;\" |\n|-\n| {{IPA|&#124;\u0254\u02d0r&#124;}}\n|\n|\n| ''t'''\u00e5r'''ne''\n| style=\"text-align: left;\" |\n|-\n| {{IPA|&#124;\u0254\u02d0&#124;}}\n|\n|\n| {{IPA|/\u0254\u02d0/}}\n| {{IPA|[\u0254\u031d\u02d0]}}\n| {{IPA|[\u0254\u033d\u02d0]}}\n| ''m'''\u00e5'''le''\n| style=\"text-align: left;\" |\n|-\n| {{IPA|&#124;\u0259&#124;}}\n|\n|\n| {{IPA|/\u0259/}}\n| {{IPA|[\u0259]}}\n| {{IPA|[\u0259]}}\n| ''hopp'''e'''''\n| style=\"text-align: left;\" |\n|-\n| {{IPA|&#124;\u0259r&#124;}}\n|\n|\n| rowspan=\"3\" | {{IPA|/\u0250/}}\n| rowspan=\"3\" | {{IPA|[\u0250]}}\n| rowspan=\"3\" | {{IPA|[\u0252\u033d]}}\n| ''fatt'''er'''''\n| style=\"text-align: left;\" |\n|-\n| {{IPA|&#124;r\u0259&#124;}}\n|\n|\n| ''tu'''re'''''\n| rowspan=\"2\" style=\"text-align: left;\" | After long vowels.{{sfnp|Basb\u00f8ll|2005|pp=72, 81}}\n|-\n| {{IPA|&#124;r\u0259r&#124;}}\n|\n|\n| ''tu'''rer'''''\n|-\n| {{IPA|&#124;j\u0259&#124;}}\n|\n|\n| rowspan=\"2\" | {{IPA|/j\u0259/}}\n| rowspan=\"2\" | {{IPA|[\u026a]}}\n| rowspan=\"2\" | {{IPA|[\u026a]}}\n| ''ve'''je'''''\n| rowspan=\"11\" style=\"text-align: left;\" | See {{section link||Schwa-assimilation}}.\n|-\n| {{IPA|&#124;\u0261\u0259&#124;}}\n|\n|\n| ''ja'''ge'''''\n|-\n| {{IPA|&#124;v\u0259&#124;}}\n|\n|\n| {{IPA|/v\u0259/}}\n| {{IPA|[\u028a]}}\n| {{IPA|[\u028a]}}\n| ''ha'''ve'''''\n|-\n| {{IPA|&#124;\u0259d&#124;}}\n|\n|\n| {{IPA|/\u0259\u00f0/}}\n| rowspan=\"2\" | {{IPA|[\u00f0\u0329]}}\n| rowspan=\"2\" | {{IPA|[\u00f0\u0329\u02d5\u02d7\u02e0]}}\n| ''m\u00e5n'''ed'''''\n|-\n| {{IPA|&#124;d\u0259&#124;}}\n|\n|\n| {{IPA|/\u00f0\u0259/}}\n| ''ba'''de'''''\n|-\n| {{IPA|&#124;\u0259l&#124;}}\n|\n|\n| {{IPA|/\u0259l/}}\n| rowspan=\"2\" | {{IPA|[l\u0329]}}\n| rowspan=\"2\" | {{IPA|[l\u0329]}}\n| ''gamm'''el'''''\n|-\n| {{IPA|&#124;l\u0259&#124;}}\n|\n|\n| {{IPA|/l\u0259/}}\n| ''ta'''le'''''\n|-\n| {{IPA|&#124;n\u0259&#124;}}\n|\n|\n| {{IPA|/n\u0259/}}\n| rowspan=\"2\" | {{IPA|[n\u0329]}}\n| rowspan=\"2\" | {{IPA|[n\u0329]}}\n| ''h\u00e5'''ne'''''\n|-\n| rowspan=\"3\" | {{IPA|&#124;\u0259n&#124;}}\n|\n|\n| rowspan=\"3\" | {{IPA|/\u0259n/}}\n| ''hest'''en'''''\n|-\n|\n|\n| {{IPA|[m\u0329]}}\n| {{IPA|[m\u0329]}}\n| ''hopp'''en'''''\n|-\n|\n|\n| {{IPA|[\u014b\u030d]}}\n| {{IPA|[\u014b\u030d]}}\n| ''pakk'''en'''''\n|}\n\nThe three way distinction in front rounded vowels {{IPA|/y \u00f8 \u0153/}} is upheld only before nasals, e.g. {{IPA|/syns s\u00f8n\u02c0s s\u0153ns/}} ''synes, synds, s\u00f8ns'' ('seems', 'sin's', 'son's'). Furthermore, there are only three words where {{IPA|/y/}} occurs before a nasal in a stressed syllable: ''synes, brynje, hymne'' ('seems, armor, hymn').{{sfnp|Basb\u00f8ll|2005|p=51}}{{failed verification|date=February 2017}}<!--Basb\u00f8ll gives some of these examples on that page, but doesn't make any of these claims.-->\n\n{{IPA|/a/}} and {{IPA|/a\u02d0/}} on one hand and {{IPA|/\u0251/}} and {{IPA|/\u0251\u02d0/}} on the other are largely in complementary distribution. However, a two-phoneme interpretation can be justified with reference to the unexpected vowel quality in words like ''andre'' {{IPA|/\u02c8andr\u0250/}} 'others' or ''anderledes'' {{IPA|/\u02c8an\u0250\u02ccle\u02d0\u00f0\u0259s/}} 'different', and an increasing number of loanwords.{{sfnp|Basb\u00f8ll|2005|pp=50\u20131}}\n\nThe vowel system is unstable, and according to at least one study,{{sfnp|Ejstrup|Hansen|2004}} the contemporary spoken language might be experiencing a merger of several of these vowels. The following vowel pairs may be merged by some speakers, leading in some cases to phonemic mergers:\n* {{IPA|[\u028a]}} with {{IPA|[o]}}, leading to a variable merger of {{IPA|/v\u0259/}} and {{IPA|/o/}} (the former can be {{IPA|[w\u0259]}} or {{IPA|[w\u028a]}} instead, in which case no merger takes place).{{sfnp|Basb\u00f8ll|2005|p=58}}\n* {{IPA|[e\u031d]}} with {{IPA|[e]}}, which is phonemic if the allophones appearing in {{IPA|/r/}}-contexts are analyzed as {{IPA|/a/}} and {{IPA|/\u0251/}}.{{sfnp|Ejstrup|Hansen|2004}}\n* {{IPA|[e\u031d\u02d0]}} with {{IPA|[e\u02d0]}}, which is phonemic if the allophones appearing in {{IPA|/r/}}-contexts are analyzed as {{IPA|/a\u02d0/}} and {{IPA|/\u0251\u02d0/}}.{{sfnp|Ejstrup|Hansen|2004}}\n* {{IPA|/\u025b\u02d0/}} with {{IPA|/a\u02d0/}}{{sfnp|Ejstrup|Hansen|2004}}\n* {{IPA|[\u00f8]}} with {{IPA|[\u0153\u031d]}}, leading to phonemization of the {{IPA|[\u0153]}} allophone.{{sfnp|Ejstrup|Hansen|2004}}\n* {{IPA|[\u00f8\u02d0]}} with {{IPA|[\u0153\u031d\u02d0]}}.{{sfnp|Ejstrup|Hansen|2004}}\n* {{IPA|[o]}} with {{IPA|[\u0254\u031d]}}, so that {{IPA|/o/}} has only one allophone.{{sfnp|Ejstrup|Hansen|2004}}\n* {{IPA|/o\u02d0/}} with {{IPA|/\u0254\u02d0/}}{{sfnp|Ejstrup|Hansen|2004}}\n* {{IPA|/\u0250/}} with {{IPA|/\u028c/}}{{sfnp|Basb\u00f8ll|2005|p=58}}\n\n{{clear}}\n\n==Schwa-assimilation==\nIn addition to {{IPA|/\u0250/}}, which stems from the fusion of {{IPA|{{!}}\u0259r{{!}}}}, {{IPA|{{!}}r\u0259{{!}}}}, or {{IPA|{{!}}r\u0259r{{!}}}}, {{IPA|/\u0259/}} assimilates to adjacent [[sonorant]]s in a variety of ways:{{sfnp|Gr\u00f8nnum|2005|pp=186\u20137}}\n\n* {{IPA|/\u0259/}} assimilates to preceding long vowels: {{IPA|/\u02c8di\u02d0\u0259/}} \u2192 {{IPA|[\u02c8ti\u02d0i]}} ''die'' 'nurse', {{IPA|/\u02c8du\u02d0\u0259/}} \u2192 {{IPA|[\u02c8tu\u02d0u]}} ''due'' 'pigeon'.{{sfnp|Gr\u00f8nnum|2005|p=186}}\n* {{IPA|/j\u0259/}} after a long vowel other than {{IPA|/i\u02d0, y\u02d0/}} and {{IPA|/v\u0259/}} after a long vowel other than {{IPA|/u\u02d0/}} become monophthongs {{IPA|[\u026a, \u028a]}}: {{IPA|/\u02c8l\u025b\u02d0j\u0259/}} \u2192 {{IPA|[\u02c8le\u02d0\u026a]}} ''l\u00e6ge'' 'doctor', {{IPA|/\u02c8l\u0254\u02d0v\u0259/}} \u2192 {{IPA|[\u02c8l\u0254\u031d\u02d0\u028a]}} ''l\u00e5ge'' 'gate'.{{sfnp|Gr\u00f8nnum|2005|pp=186\u20137}} In innovative varieties, the vowels may become shorter: {{IPA|[\u02c8lej\u026a], [\u02c8l\u0254\u031dw\u028a]}}.{{sfnp|Gr\u00f8nnum|2005|p=269}}\n* A sonorant consonant ({{IPA|/\u00f0, l, m, n, \u014b/}}) and {{IPA|/\u0259/}}, in either order, become a [[syllabic consonant]] {{IPA|[\u00f0\u0329, l\u0329, m\u0329, n\u0329, \u014b\u030d]}}.{{sfnp|Gr\u00f8nnum|2005|pp=301\u20132}}\n** It is longer after a short vowel than after a long one: {{IPA|/\u02c8ba\u02d0\u00f0\u0259/}} \u2192 {{IPA|[\u02c8p\u00e6\u02d0\u00f0\u0329]}} ''bade'' 'bathe', {{IPA|/\u02c8hu\u02d0l\u0259/}} \u2192 {{IPA|[\u02c8hu\u02d0l\u0329]}} ''hule'' 'cave', {{IPA|/\u02c8sbi\u00f0\u0259/}} \u2192 {{IPA|[\u02c8spi\u00f0\u00f0\u0329]}} ''spidde'' 'spear', {{IPA|/\u02c8kul\u0259/}} \u2192 {{IPA|[\u02c8k\u02b0ull\u0329]}} ''kulde'' 'cold'.{{sfnp|Gr\u00f8nnum|2005|p=187}}\n** When {{IPA|/\u0259/}} is placed between two sonorant consonants, the second becomes syllabic: {{IPA|/\u02c8sa\u00f0\u0259l/}} \u2192 {{IPA|[\u02c8s\u00e6\u00f0l\u0329]}} ''saddel'' 'saddle', {{IPA|/\u02c8hyl\u0259\u00f0/}} \u2192 {{IPA|[\u02c8hyl\u00f0\u0329]}} ''hyldet'' 'praised'.{{sfnp|Gr\u00f8nnum|2005|p=187}}\n** The place of a syllabic nasal ({{IPA|/\u0259n/}}) assimilates to that of the preceding consonant: {{IPA|/\u02c8l\u0251b\u0259n/}} \u2192 {{IPA|[\u02c8l\u0251pm\u0329]}} ''lappen'' 'patches', {{IPA|/\u02c8l\u0251\u0261\u0259n/}} \u2192 {{IPA|[\u02c8l\u0251k\u014b\u030d]}} ''lakken'' 'varnishes'.{{sfnp|Gr\u00f8nnum|2005|p=302}}\n\nIn casual speech, {{IPA|/\u0259/}} may also be elided after an [[obstruent]]. If that occurs after a long vowel, the syllable with the elided {{IPA|/\u0259/}} may be retained by lengthening the vowel preceding the consonant: {{IPA|/\u02c8h\u0254\u02d0b\u0259/}} \u2192 {{IPA|[\u02c8h\u0254\u031d\u02d0(\u0254\u031d)p]}} ''h\u00e5be'' 'hope'.{{sfnp|Gr\u00f8nnum|2005|p=187}}\n\n==Prosody==\n\n===Stress===\nUnlike the neighboring Mainland Scandinavian languages Swedish and Norwegian, the prosody of Danish does not have phonemic pitch. [[stress (linguistics)|Stress]] is phonemic and distinguishes words like ''billigst'' {{IPA|[\u02c8pilist]}} ('cheapest') and ''bilist'' {{IPA|[pi\u02c8list]}} ('car driver'). In syntactic phrases, verbs lose their stress (and st\u00f8d, if any) with an [[Object (grammar)|object]] without a definite or indefinite [[Article (grammar)|article]]: e.g. ''\u02c8Jens \u02c8spiser et \u02c8br\u00f8d'' {{IPA|[\u02c8jens \u02c8spi\u02c0s\u0250 e\u031dt \u02c8p\u0281\u0153\u031d\u00f0\u02c0]}} ('Jens eats a loaf') ~ ''\u02c8Jens spiser \u02c8br\u00f8d'' {{IPA|[\u02c8jens spis\u0250 \u02c8p\u0281\u0153\u031d\u00f0\u02c0]}} ('Jens eats bread'). In names, only the surname is stressed, e.g. {{IPA|[joh\u00e6n\u0329lui\u02d0s\u0259 \u02c8h\u0251j\u02ccp\u025b\u0250\u032f\u02c0]}} ''[[Johanne Luise Heiberg]]''.{{sfnp|Gr\u00f8nnum|1998|p=104}}\n\n===St\u00f8d===\n{{main|St\u00f8d}}\nIn a number of words with stress on the final syllable, long vowels and sonorants may exhibit a prosodic feature called ''st\u00f8d'' ('thrust').{{sfnp|Haberland|1994|p=318}} Acoustically, vowels with st\u00f8d tend to be a little shorter{{sfnp|Haberland|1994|p=318}} and feature [[creaky voice]].{{sfnp|Basb\u00f8ll|2005|p=83}} Historically, this feature operated as a redundant aspect of stress on monosyllabic words that had either a long vowel or final voiced consonant. Since the creation of new monosyllabic words, this association with monosyllables is no longer as strong. Some other tendencies include:\n*Polysyllabic words with the nominal definite suffix ''-et'' may exhibit st\u00f8d{{sfnp|Haberland|1994|p=318}}\n*Polysyllabic loanwords with final stress on either a long vowel or a vowel with a final sonorant typically feature st\u00f8d{{sfnp|Haberland|1994|p=318}}\n\nDiphthongs with an underlying long vowel always have st\u00f8d.{{sfnp|Gr\u00f8nnum|2005|p=294}}\n\n== Text sample ==\nThe sample text is an indistinct reading of the first sentence of [[The North Wind and the Sun]].\n\n===Orthographic version===\nNordenvinden og solen kom engang i strid om, hvem af dem der var den st\u00e6rkeste.{{sfnp|Gr\u00f8nnum|1998|p=104}}\n\n===Broad phonetic transcription===\n{{IPA|[\u02c8no\u0250\u032f\u0250n\u02ccve\u031dn\u02c0n\u0329 \u028c \u02c8so\u02c0l\u0329n k\u02b0\u028cm e\u031d\u014b\u02c8k\u0251\u014b\u02c0 i \u02c8st\u0281i\u00f0\u02c0 \u02c8\u028cm\u02c0 \u02c8vem\u02c0 \u02c8\u00e6 pm\u0329 t\u0251 v\u0251 tn\u0329 \u02c8st\u025b\u0250\u032fk\u0259st\u0259]}}{{sfnp|Gr\u00f8nnum|1998|p=104}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|20em}}\n\n==Bibliography==\n{{refbegin|30em}}\n* {{citation\n|last=Abrahams\n|first=Henrik\n|year=1949\n|title=\u00c9tudes phon\u00e9tiques sur les tendances \u00e9volutives des occlusives germaniques\n|publisher=Aarhus University Press\n}}\n* {{citation\n|last=Allan\n|first=Robin\n|last2=Holmes\n|first2=Philip\n|last3=Lundsk\u00e6r-Nielsen\n|first3=Tom\n|year=2011\n|orig-year=First published 2000\n|title=Danish: An Essential Grammar\n|edition=2nd\n|publisher=Routledge\n|place=Abingdon\n|isbn=978-0-203-87800-2\n}}\n* {{citation\n|last=Basb\u00f8ll\n|first=Hans\n|authorlink=Hans Basb\u00f8ll\n|year=2005\n|title=The Phonology of Danish\n|publisher=Oxford University Press\n|place=Oxford\n|isbn=0-203-97876-5\n}}\n* {{citation\n|last1=Brink\n|first1=Lars\n|last2=Lund\n|first2=J\u00f8rn\n|last3=Heger\n|first3=Steffen\n|last4=J\u00f8rgensen\n|first4=J. Normann\n|year=1991